'''Kinomiya Shrine''' (きのみやじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Hatsuma, {{ill|lt=Izu|Q696840|qid=Q696840|1=Izu, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|qid=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}.

To distinguish it from other Kinomiya Shrines, it is also called '''Hatsuma Kinomiya Shrine''' (はつま きのみやじんじゃ)<ref name="tennen">[http://www.city.izu.shizuoka.jp/gyousei/gyousei_detail000109.html City-designated Natural Monuments] - Izu City</ref>.

=== Overview ===
The shrine buildings, which had fallen into ruin, are said to have been rebuilt in the {{ill|lt=Nanboku-chō period|Q264012|qid=Q264012|lt=Jōwa|1=Nanboku-chō period}} era (1345-1349), and the shrine came to serve as the general tutelary shrine of the 16 Ōmi villages (most of the former {{ill|lt=Nakaizu Town|Q6960169|qid=Q6960169|1=Nakaizu, Shizuoka}} area)<ref name="tennen"/><ref name="yuisho">Precinct history board</ref>.

The pattern of a “Kinomiya Shrine” as part of {{ill|lt=Kinomiya worship|Q11296898|qid=Q11296898|1=Kinomiya Faith}} being brought into a place named “Hachiman” is similar to nearby {{ill|lt=Hachimangū Kinomiya Shrine|Q11390944|qid=Q11390944|1=Hachimangū Kinomiya Shrine}} in Yawatano, {{ill|lt=Itō|Q721163|qid=Q721163|1=Itō, Shizuoka}}.

Also, in works such as ''{{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō Kōshō Dadai|Q11588823|qid=Q11588823|1=Jinmyōchō Kōshō Dodai}}'', it is named, along with {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kawazu Kinomiya Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} (Sugihokowake-no-Mikoto Shrine) in {{ill|lt=Kawazu|Q1203861|qid=Q1203861|1=Kawazu, Shizuoka}}, as a candidate shrine for “Sugihokowake-no-Mikoto Shrine” in the {{ill|lt=list of Shikinaisha in Izu Province|Q11380552|qid=Q11380552|lt=Shikinaisha of Izu|1=List of Shikinaisha in Izu Province}}. (In the northwestern nearby area, Kami-Shiraiwa, there is also {{ill|lt=Ōmiya Shrine (Izu)|Q113679907|qid=Q113679907|lt=Ōmiya Shrine|1=Omiya Shrine (Izu)}}, a candidate shrine for another Shikinaisha, “Ōasa Shrine.”)

It has a distinctive landscape in which a torii and approach are formed between road and rice fields, and at the entrance to the precincts stand giant cedars designated as city natural monuments<ref name="tennen"/>.

